621
00:59:25,815 --> 00:59:28,497
You know that that's not what we're trying to do, Ron.

622
00:59:28,777 --> 00:59:31,338
You're really kind of convoluting the process.

623
00:59:32,519 --> 00:59:35,601
We have a task to make a recommendation to the mayor.

624
00:59:36,341 --> 00:59:38,743
And it's going to take us about a year.

625
00:59:38,803 --> 00:59:41,444
We're going to take us a year to do it, right?

626
00:59:41,985 --> 00:59:42,185
Yeah.

627
00:59:43,065 --> 00:59:45,225
We have to find out what the people want.

628
00:59:45,646 --> 00:59:46,926
What are you going to do after this?

629
00:59:47,166 --> 00:59:49,746
We send out the survey, next month we get the results.

630
00:59:50,066 --> 00:59:51,247
Then where do we go from there?

631
00:59:51,567 --> 00:59:53,687
Well, I don't think we're going to get the results next month.

632
00:59:54,827 --> 00:59:57,708
I think it's going to take many months to get the information.

633
00:59:58,248 --> 01:00:00,949
We'll talk about how long we want to keep the survey open.

634
01:00:00,989 --> 01:00:02,449
That's another thing we're going to talk about.

635
01:00:02,749 --> 01:00:07,530
I just want to on record saying I think it's premature to start asking those questions and not having

636
01:00:08,093 --> 01:00:12,597
input, more input from focus groups, presentations and discussion.

637
01:00:12,937 --> 01:00:18,803
I just, that's my record and you know, I just wanna be on the record of saying that.

638
01:00:19,163 --> 01:00:20,204
Okay, thanks.

639
01:00:20,384 --> 01:00:20,825
Thank you.

640
01:00:21,425 --> 01:00:27,270
Let's finish going through the survey and then we'll talk about whether we want, whether or when we wanna move forward with it.

641
01:00:27,851 --> 01:00:33,956
So we had a, basically these are sort of foundational questions, right?

642
01:00:35,745 --> 01:00:42,874
mayor, you know, the form of government, mayor, city manager, term of the mayor, composition of the city council.

643
01:00:42,934 --> 01:00:47,019
This is about composition of the school committee.

644
01:00:47,039 --> 01:00:53,207
The, you know, the little bit of information is that

645
01:00:54,466 --> 01:01:08,016
Medford is, while Medford City Council is not in step with the rest of the state in terms of not having ward representation and being so small, the school committee is actually, is in step with the rest of the state.

646
01:01:08,096 --> 01:01:17,403
So because state trends, most school committees are at large, and seven is a pretty common size.

647
01:01:17,523 --> 01:01:20,926
So the question here is, should they remain at large?

648
01:01:21,106 --> 01:01:23,168
Should there be a combination of ward and at large?

649
01:01:26,159 --> 01:01:30,102
it does occur to me that we could actually have all at ward.

650
01:01:30,483 --> 01:01:34,986
I mean, all ward with the school committee because the mayor being the ninth member.

651
01:01:36,728 --> 01:01:39,670
So we could add that question, right?

652
01:01:41,752 --> 01:01:53,241
Because, um, well, yeah, I guess, um, if we want another question, it would be, do we want the mayor to be a member of the school committee?

653
01:01:54,202 --> 01:01:54,302
Um,

654
01:01:54,782 --> 01:02:00,864
you know, which is, I think, something that, you know, we need to address as well.

655
01:02:00,924 --> 01:02:07,207
We do need to, but I have to double check this, but I think it's in state law.

656
01:02:08,667 --> 01:02:15,470
Whether the mayor is chair of the school committee, I could be wrong about that, but we should look into that.

657
01:02:15,890 --> 01:02:20,712
No, but I also thought that Collins Center said something about board representation on school committee.

658
01:02:20,832 --> 01:02:24,453
I'm not sure if they said you can't do it or whatever, but we should definitely check it.

659
01:02:24,991 --> 01:02:33,374
I'm positive that they didn't say you can't, but it is definitely not, it's not the way ward representation is common on city councils.

660
01:02:33,434 --> 01:02:38,596
It's not common on school committees, but there are school committees that have ward representation.

661
01:02:38,896 --> 01:02:39,936
So it is possible.

662
01:02:42,657 --> 01:02:46,158
Whether the mayor has to be on the school committee, we should look at that.

663
01:02:47,159 --> 01:02:50,840
I think it's state law, but I don't want to say for sure.

664
01:02:50,860 --> 01:02:52,981
So research that,

665
01:02:53,715 --> 01:02:59,398
It's definitely not required that the mayor be chair of the school committee.

666
01:03:00,319 --> 01:03:07,343
Okay, this is about term length for city councilors, and this is about term length for school committee members.

667
01:03:08,044 --> 01:03:12,066
And then there's a question about the chair of school committee of the mayor.

668
01:03:15,010 --> 01:03:23,894
In comparable Massachusetts cities, I think it's about 50-50 with the mayor being the chair of the school committee.

669
01:03:26,795 --> 01:03:35,419
And in other scenarios, the mayor is a member of the school committee, but the committee can elect their own chair.

670
01:03:36,700 --> 01:03:38,561
So that's what these questions reflect.

671
01:03:38,901 --> 01:03:41,682
Should the mayor remain as chair of the school committee?

672
01:03:46,747 --> 01:03:47,487
term limits.

673
01:03:50,208 --> 01:03:54,010
I mean, you know, people talk about them.

674
01:03:54,070 --> 01:03:58,672
It's something that I think we should ask about.

675
01:04:00,352 --> 01:04:09,115
And then there's questions about the term limit, also city council, also school committee, and then comes balance of power.

676
01:04:10,256 --> 01:04:12,537
We want to get into the nitty gritty in this of

677
01:04:13,666 --> 01:04:22,072
what we think the term limit should be, two years, four years, six years, or just, yes, there should be, no, there shouldn't.

678
01:04:22,633 --> 01:04:30,499
Okay, so just, so we could revise these questions to- And then they trim things for us?

679
01:04:30,579 --> 01:04:36,103
So for the term limits.

680
01:04:37,404 --> 01:04:37,664
Wait a minute.

681
01:04:37,704 --> 01:04:38,725
May I make a suggestion?

682
01:04:38,745 --> 01:04:40,186
Okay, for a term limit, yeah, go ahead.

683
01:04:40,787 --> 01:04:42,388
So that would take out this question here.

684
01:04:42,880 --> 01:04:52,602
Now, if you just did a yes or no on the term limits, right, then you can go to what ROM is proposing, more dialogue, focus groups.

685
01:04:53,342 --> 01:04:58,824
And then in those groups, you can say, yeah, we, you know, the citizens want term limits.

686
01:04:59,124 --> 01:05:00,664
How long do you think they should be?

687
01:05:00,984 --> 01:05:02,585
And then you can get like a consensus.

688
01:05:03,265 --> 01:05:12,627
And, you know, then the committee can, you know, say, well, you know, we talked to a lot of people and most people think three terms for the mayor is more than enough.

689
01:05:13,327 --> 01:05:16,690
Then we really have the will of the people.

690
01:05:17,350 --> 01:05:17,790
I agree.

691
01:05:17,850 --> 01:05:24,095
I think a yes or no on the term limits, we could probably cut those other questions out.

692
01:05:25,468 --> 01:05:33,393
I mean, balance of power was definitely one of the issues that came up as a big issue at our meeting last week.

693
01:05:35,074 --> 01:05:48,282
So this is basically, so this first question, for instance, is one of the non-specific questions that there's been some discussion about in terms of the effectiveness of those questions.

694
01:05:49,386 --> 01:06:05,310
Um, basically it's just a broad question asking us, you know, getting, trying to get people's perceptions of whether they think the mayor has too much power or the city council has too much power or, or what do, can we do away with that question?

695
01:06:05,330 --> 01:06:10,692
I mean, you know, it also is followed up.

696
01:06:11,223 --> 01:06:16,507
by if you answered A or B, please indicate your ideas on balancing Medford's governmental power.

697
01:06:16,567 --> 01:06:25,173
So I mean, this survey also at the end, we'll have chances for people to give longer input and hopefully we'll get some of that.

698
01:06:26,954 --> 01:06:38,422
But I guess in the interest of trimming, do we wanna just take out the sort of broad question about people's perceptions about the balance of power in the city?

699
01:06:39,462 --> 01:06:40,363
Yeah, I think that's more,

700
01:06:40,896 --> 01:06:42,076
Feelings type thing.

701
01:06:46,557 --> 01:06:49,938
Yeah, OK.

702
01:06:50,098 --> 01:06:53,519
So then we go to the specific question department heads.

703
01:06:55,219 --> 01:06:59,800
And then there's the another question about board committees and commissions.

704
01:07:03,381 --> 01:07:07,141
I think I think some of these questions are might be getting a little too far in the weeds.

705
01:07:09,102 --> 01:07:10,262
You know, especially for me.

706
01:07:10,877 --> 01:07:12,380
they address balance of power.

707
01:07:12,480 --> 01:07:16,809
So yeah, but I mean,

708
01:07:18,647 --> 01:07:22,868
But there's also practical information that people would need to make that decision.

709
01:07:22,908 --> 01:07:40,431
Like, would the general public understand the difficulty a mayor has in hiring folks who know that they have to go then to be kind of grilled by a city council and either be voted in or voted down?

710
01:07:40,752 --> 01:07:42,512
A lot of people would choose not

711
01:07:43,192 --> 01:07:52,975
to put themselves in that position, and it can make it very difficult for the city to retain good, qualified folks at City Hall.

712
01:07:53,015 --> 01:08:03,738
So, like, people have to know a little bit about that particular question before I think they can make a kind of an informed kind of decision.

713
01:08:03,798 --> 01:08:11,220
Like, do they know that, like, if you give the city council this power, it could have a negative

714
01:08:11,760 --> 01:08:15,484
impact on the process.

715
01:08:15,985 --> 01:08:31,282
Or maybe they might be able to weed out a bad choice, but I think that's a decision that people have to have a little bit more information before they can say, yeah, that's a good idea, or I support that, or I don't.

716
01:08:31,758 --> 01:08:38,165
Okay, one of these questions speaks directly to one of the amendments that City Council is currently proposing.

717
01:08:38,245 --> 01:08:45,992
So we had earlier talked about, do we want to include those questions and this would be including one of them.

718
01:08:46,673 --> 01:08:51,838
The one about approving appointments to boards, committees and commissions.

719
01:08:53,060 --> 01:08:54,361
So I just wanna throw that out there.

720
01:08:55,017 --> 01:09:08,227
Well, I guess I would come back with how it's worded would be very important if you can put it in a neutral kind of way.

721
01:09:09,628 --> 01:09:13,951
Because at the face of the question, it sounds like, sure, let the city council.

722
01:09:14,352 --> 01:09:19,375
If I didn't think about it, I'd say, yeah, why not?

723
01:09:19,535 --> 01:09:21,757
Let the city council approve everybody.

724
01:09:22,358 --> 01:09:24,219
What would make it more neutral?

725
01:09:29,900 --> 01:09:34,942
What do you think would make Trump?

726
01:09:35,442 --> 01:09:57,230
Let's see, without asking an open-ended, I'm trying to get to like not open-ended kind of questions where people, you know, kind of give kind of opinion rather than kind of, I'd have to think about that because I'm not sure if there is an easy way to do that without doing like a whole tutorial on it, you know.

727
01:09:57,928 --> 01:09:59,068
Uh, exactly.

728
01:09:59,188 --> 01:10:03,110
So, I mean, my feeling is that this is as neutral as you can get.

729
01:10:03,150 --> 01:10:06,371
It's state the fact and then it asks a yes or no question.

730
01:10:07,011 --> 01:10:24,357
But, um, but even if we got this back and we and what we heard, what we got from the survey and what we heard from our focus groups and all that is because we did hear a lot of people last week saying that they feel that the city council needs more power.

731
01:10:24,377 --> 01:10:24,418
Um,

732
01:10:27,042 --> 01:10:43,435
Even if we got this back and it felt like overwhelmingly people wanted the city council to have the power to approve appointments, it would still be our job to look at the details of that if we decided to go ahead with it.

733
01:10:44,042 --> 01:10:46,284
No, but I didn't hear that in the meeting.

734
01:10:46,605 --> 01:10:47,605
I didn't get that feeling.

735
01:10:48,106 --> 01:10:49,447
I didn't get that feeling at all.

736
01:10:49,567 --> 01:10:56,394
So I don't know if I was kind of, I heard some people talk about the frustration with the city council.

737
01:10:56,854 --> 01:11:05,042
I didn't really hear anyone talking about, they wanted them to be more participate and have kind of have more input.

738
01:11:05,242 --> 01:11:07,324
I didn't see anybody saying that,

739
01:11:08,285 --> 01:11:16,829
you know, the city council needs more power and they want them to, uh, to kind of make this type of, uh, you know, decision.

740
01:11:17,610 --> 01:11:18,190
Um, okay.

741
01:11:18,310 --> 01:11:27,575
I mean, I, I thought I heard balance of power as a concern and, um, we've, it's also in the, um, document we have of the, uh,

742
01:11:28,012 --> 01:11:34,934
feedback on the feedback form and emails, it's been an issue in almost every single one that we've gotten, so.

743
01:11:35,454 --> 01:11:56,781
There was a talk about balance of power definitely between the mayor and the city council, but I think it was more certainly surrounding the budget, which is a big, big conversation, but I feel like I'm gonna take a step back for a minute and

744
01:11:58,972 --> 01:12:10,580
Um, a lot of people, I just feel like some of this is getting into the weeds because you're putting this out and let's say we put out, you know, 5,000 surveys.

745
01:12:12,001 --> 01:12:16,244
You know, most people don't watch city council and school committee meetings.

746
01:12:16,464 --> 01:12:23,869
Most people don't have a lot of awareness of how the government runs.

747
01:12:23,969 --> 01:12:25,450
It just sort of does.

748
01:12:26,651 --> 01:12:27,772
And, you know,

749
01:12:29,635 --> 01:12:40,372
For example, I mean, the government, how the city government runs impacts every citizen in the community, but I don't think most people.

750
01:12:42,022 --> 01:12:50,984
give it a whole lot of thought unless they're either really paying attention like some of us do or they run into an issue.

751
01:12:53,104 --> 01:13:07,927
I'm going to give you a sort of a strange example, but the Office of Planning and Sustainability put out a survey a few months back about waste and trash and things.

752
01:13:09,008 --> 01:13:10,808
Well, we all put out trash.

753
01:13:11,632 --> 01:13:15,393
you know, every, whatever day of the week your trash day is.

754
01:13:16,293 --> 01:13:24,815
And that is something tangible that, you know, we can sort of all relate to.

755
01:13:25,835 --> 01:13:31,756
Trash pickup impacts every single one of us too, just the same as how the city government operates.

756
01:13:32,056 --> 01:13:34,377
But it's something that people pay a whole lot more attention to.

757
01:13:34,917 --> 01:13:36,557
The trash gets picked up or it doesn't.

758
01:13:36,597 --> 01:13:38,397
The leaves get picked up or it doesn't.

759
01:13:38,838 --> 01:13:41,118
You know, how come we don't have a, you know,

760
01:13:41,800 --> 01:13:47,084
a leaf pickup in December because my tree is still falling at the beginning of December.

761
01:13:47,104 --> 01:13:53,028
I think with some of this stuff, they don't know anything about department heads.

762
01:13:53,148 --> 01:14:00,934
Some people in the city may not have ever dealt with a department head in the city for anything.

763
01:14:03,010 --> 01:14:06,174
We, you know, we were talking, we are, we are one of the.

764
01:14:06,855 --> 01:14:12,503
Well, we're committee, but boards and commissions for, you know, kind of the umbrella of it.

765
01:14:13,824 --> 01:14:17,749
You know, I mentioned the other night in response to somebody's question that.

766
01:14:18,840 --> 01:14:24,125
Medford has probably a dozen boards and commissions that citizens serves on.

767
01:14:24,145 --> 01:14:26,487
And I've mentioned that to other people before too.

768
01:14:26,927 --> 01:14:28,629
I don't think most people even know that.

769
01:14:29,470 --> 01:14:33,793
So I think we're getting a bit too far into the weeds.

770
01:14:33,913 --> 01:14:44,002
I think the first survey that goes out has to kind of, you know, cater to the broadest issues.

771
01:14:45,266 --> 01:14:45,646
Okay.

772
01:14:46,467 --> 01:14:48,648
Kind of the lowest time in denominator.

773
01:14:49,228 --> 01:14:52,489
I don't know how many surveys we're going to be putting out.

774
01:14:52,890 --> 01:14:59,733
I don't know that we can, I mean, we can definitely do more than one, but I don't know that we should try to do a bunch.

775
01:15:00,513 --> 01:15:06,036
These questions are going to have to be answered by our committee, whether or not we put them in the survey.

776
01:15:06,096 --> 01:15:07,436
So I just want to put that out there.

777
01:15:07,877 --> 01:15:11,098
Can I just make one quick, one more statement?

778
01:15:11,218 --> 01:15:11,878
I'm Italian.

779
01:15:11,898 --> 01:15:13,119
So I like to have the last word.

780
01:15:13,705 --> 01:15:16,408
But I'm also married, so I know it's not always doable.

781
01:15:16,488 --> 01:15:27,819
But I think Eunice and Anthony are making my point in saying that the knowledge base is not necessarily there to give justified responses to some of these questions.

782
01:15:28,540 --> 01:15:30,462
So why wouldn't we look at

783
01:15:31,572 --> 01:15:36,656
maybe listing 25 items and having folks pick what's important to them.

784
01:15:36,916 --> 01:15:38,377
Then the survey gives us this.

785
01:15:38,837 --> 01:15:45,122
It gives us 60% of the people want to discuss the mayor issue.

786
01:15:45,142 --> 01:15:46,903
60% want us to discuss this or that.

787
01:15:47,003 --> 01:15:51,406
And we come up with a list so that you just quickly look at the list and say, this is important to me.

788
01:15:51,826 --> 01:15:53,187
And you check as many as you want.

789
01:15:53,508 --> 01:15:56,450
And at the end, you have a space that said, these are the other issues I want.

790
01:15:57,328 --> 01:16:00,849
What we're trying, we have to understand what we're trying to get out of the survey.

791
01:16:01,209 --> 01:16:04,770
And out of the survey, we should be getting what is important to the folks.

792
01:16:05,330 --> 01:16:16,874
Then we can go into the education and then we have a real true survey that says, as far as the mayor goes, I didn't realize six years term would mean this or that because I heard the discussion.

793
01:16:17,774 --> 01:16:18,874
That's what I think is fair.

794
01:16:19,054 --> 01:16:25,376
Can you be more specific and like just sort of say what kinds of, say a couple of the questions you're thinking of.

795
01:16:26,803 --> 01:16:28,504
The length of term for a mayor.

796
01:16:29,685 --> 01:16:30,785
Okay.

797
01:16:31,706 --> 01:16:33,327
How long they can stay in office.

798
01:16:33,487 --> 01:16:34,687
So we have that in there.

799
01:16:34,707 --> 01:16:36,748
I'm just saying, the question is, of these 20 issues,

800
01:16:42,761 --> 01:16:43,922
What do you want us to focus?

801
01:16:44,002 --> 01:16:45,663
What do you want us to discuss?

802
01:16:46,744 --> 01:16:49,766
So all we're saying to them is, this is important to me.

803
01:16:50,327 --> 01:16:52,228
So is the council important to you?

804
01:16:55,691 --> 01:16:57,252
Whatever it is, it gives us a list.

805
01:16:57,312 --> 01:17:00,674
And I think that's really a good thing for us to have that says,

806
01:17:01,535 --> 01:17:03,716
These are the 25 items we suggested.

807
01:17:03,736 --> 01:17:09,139
17 of those are priorities for more than 50% of our respondents.

808
01:17:09,660 --> 01:17:12,581
And then here's another 20 issues that they wrote down the bottom.

809
01:17:13,121 --> 01:17:18,404
And that gives us like a, okay, I'm sure all the issues we've talked about, boom, boom, boom.

810
01:17:18,785 --> 01:17:22,306
But that's also gonna give us a chance to say, these are our issues.

811
01:17:22,347 --> 01:17:26,149
We're gonna schedule presentation on this one, focus group on this one.

812
01:17:26,629 --> 01:17:29,590
But we're always dealing with the issues that are important to the citizens.

813
01:17:29,631 --> 01:17:30,291
And I agree with,

814
01:17:30,651 --> 01:17:31,213
with Anthony.

815
01:17:31,253 --> 01:17:35,687
I think we need to listen to the people, but what is their priority?

816
01:17:36,309 --> 01:17:37,753
In asking these questions,

817
01:17:38,935 --> 01:17:44,357
You know, we've talked about, you know, maybe folks don't have all the background they need to make a decision.

818
01:17:44,417 --> 01:17:45,677
That's not for us to decide.

819
01:17:46,078 --> 01:18:00,303
But for us is to make sure that we've done our due diligence to make sure they're educated on both sides, understand the stuff that Collins Center has taught us about these issues, and set them up so that when we do have that survey that says, do you want this or not?

820
01:18:01,196 --> 01:18:03,557
We know that we've done our due diligence to educate.

821
01:18:03,778 --> 01:18:09,861
Right now, it's not, as we've said a couple of times as we've gone through this, I'm not sure that people understand this or that.

822
01:18:10,341 --> 01:18:16,645
So to me, as I'm rethinking this, I think the survey should be, what are your top issues?

823
01:18:16,685 --> 01:18:18,146
Here's 25, do you want it?

824
01:18:18,226 --> 01:18:19,086
Yes, just check it.

825
01:18:19,567 --> 01:18:22,228
And then- So you would just ask them to check boxes.

826
01:18:22,828 --> 01:18:24,209
Whatever the topic is, right.

827
01:18:24,630 --> 01:18:28,632
